Diglyphosema anastrephae
Rhower, 1919
: 156
Lopheucoila anastrephae
;
Weld 1951
: 224
Diagnosis. Body stout. Head (
Fig. 1
) with lateral margin of occiput well defined. Eyes without pubescence. Antennae of female (
Fig. 2
) glabrous, widened towards apex and laterally compressed, club 9 ­segmented, inconspicuous. Antennae of male (
Fig. 3
) with the first flagellomere slightly curved, distally swollen, slightly longer than second. Dorsal margin of pronotal plate (
Fig. 4
) with three emarginations; sides of pronotum with longitudinal carinae. Mesoscutum (
Figs. 5 and 6
) strongly convex in profile, median mesoscutal carina present. Dorsal part of scutellum (
Fig. 6
) striate radialy; dorsoposterior part in dorsal view emarginate, four­angled posterolaterally. Scutellar plate (
Figs. 5 and 6
) small, quite elevated, with a tooth overhanging the circular pit, which is distinctly removed from the posterior margin of the plate. Mesopleuron (
Fig. 5
) with subalar pit. Metapleuron (
Fig. 5
) sculptured. Forewings (
Fig. 7
) completely hyaline, punctate, apical margin with hair fringe; marginal cell open anteriorly and partly at base; veins colourless. Metacoxa (
Fig. 8
) with a band of hairs along the posterior margin. Third abdominal tergum of metasoma (
Fig. 5
) with a thin hairy ring and two sulci striate at base; metasoma distally punctate.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Geographical distribution. Neotropical Region: Mexico , Costa Rica , Trinidad & Tobago , Panama , Venezuela , Brazil , Peru and Argentina (
Gallardo & Diaz 1999
). In Brazil it is distributed throughout the States of Mato Grosso do Sul, São Paulo, Santa Catarina (Guimarães et al . 2000 ) and Minas Gerais (new record).

